I deleted forty lines of RxJS last week and replaced them with four lines of signals.
The app did not just work the same. It worked better. Fewer bugs, fewer subscriptions to forget, fewer moments of staring at a stream trying to remember why it stopped emitting.
I am not telling you to throw RxJS away. I am telling you that for a huge amount of what we reach for RxJS to do, there is now a smaller, sharper tool sitting right next to it, and most developers have not picked it up yet.
Six features. Six real comparisons. Let us get into what actually changed.
1. signal() Instead of BehaviorSubject for Simple State
The problem
A BehaviorSubject for a piece of state that any component just needs to read and write looks like this.
export class CartService {
private countSubject = new BehaviorSubject<number>(0);
count$ = this.countSubject.asObservable(); add() {
this.countSubject.next(this.countSubject.value + 1);
}
}To read the current value anywhere, a component needs to subscribe, remember to unsubscribe, or wrap the template in an async pipe. For a single number, that is a lot of ceremony.
